\par\par \uc2 Opinion\par \b \uc2 EDITORIAL; \uc2 IMF\uc2  governance reforms are a good first step, but more are needed\b0\par\par\uc2 , IMF governance reforms are a good first step, but more are needed   \par \uc2 619 \uc2 words\par \uc2 23 December 2015\par \uc2 Business Times Singapore\par \uc2 STBT\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2015 Singapore Press Holdings Limited   \par \par \uc2 FIVE years after the \uc2 International Monetary Fund\uc2  (\uc2 IMF\uc2 ) quota and governance reforms were mooted at the G-20 economic summit in \b \highlight22\uc2 Seoul\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the \uc2 US Congress\uc2  finally adopted legislation to authorise these reforms last week.\par \par \uc2 This authorisation comes not a moment too soon. In the time that has been lost, US clout and influence in the international financial system has suffered some erosion. That erosion could continue unless even more governance reforms are put in place, and at both the \uc2 IMF\uc2  and the \uc2 World Bank\uc2  - which have dominated global multilateral finance in the post World War II era.\par \par \uc2 The main elements in the \uc2 IMF\uc2  governance reforms are:\par \par \uc2 * an increase in the quotas of all 188 \uc2 IMF\uc2  members, resulting in a doubling of the \uc2 IMF\uc2 's quota-based resources to the equivalent of around US$660 billion, from US$330 billion;\par \par \uc2 * higher quota shares (and therefore, voting power) for some emerging market and developing countries, particularly China, but also Brazil, India and Russia - all of which become among the 10 largest members of the \uc2 IMF\uc2 ;\par \par \uc2 * the abolition of appointed executive directors at the \uc2 IMF\uc2  (which was permitted in the case of countries with the five largest quotas). All directors in future will be elected; and\par \par \uc2 * protection for the voting power and quota shares of the \uc2 IMF\uc2 's poorest members.\par \par \uc2 These are all welcome changes. The quota increase will give the Fund more financial firepower to deal with crises without having to bend its rules - which it did in the case of, for example, its support for Greece, which went way beyond the \uc2 IMF\uc2 's normal lending limits. The greater allocations of quotas to large emerging market countries will give them a little more say in the Fund's activities - although the United States will retain its veto power. The abolition of appointed directors would lead to a more democratic composition of the \uc2 IMF\uc2 's board. And the protections accorded to the \uc2 IMF\uc2 's poorest members are fair, and will help promote or maintain the \uc2 IMF\uc2 's credibility and legitimacy among these needy countries.\par \par \uc2 However, even after these reforms are put in place, there is room for more. The share of some emerging economies - especially China - is still out of line with their economic size and influence. China's post-reform voting power for instance, would be at about 6 per cent of the total, less than half of its share of global gross domestic product.\par \par \uc2 A more democratic approach to not only board membership but also institutional leadership is also long overdue - not just at the \uc2 IMF\uc2  but also the \uc2 World Bank\uc2 . Historically, by custom, the \uc2 IMF\uc2  has always been headed by a European and the \uc2 World Bank\uc2  by an American. This has now become an anachronism that has no place in the contemporary world. Hopefully, it will change when the leadership of the \uc2 IMF\uc2  is up for renewal next year.\par \par \uc2 Leadership aside, the image and legitimacy of the \uc2 IMF\uc2  is also compromised by the perception that its primary agenda is to serve creditor interests - which was reinforced in its dealings with the eurozone crisis. The IMF-supported programmes in troubled economies (which have largely failed to achieve their targets) were - and still are - perceived as pro-creditor and anti-growth. This is not dissimilar to how the \uc2 IMF\uc2  was perceived in Asia during the Asian crisis of 1998. The quota and governance reforms that the \uc2 US Congress\uc2  has finally authorised are a positive step forward. But more steps will be needed if the \uc2 IMF\uc2  is to become a truly global, democratic and effective institution.\par \par \uc2 Document STBT000020151222ebcn0000n\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw107\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal1605\pichgoal600
