\par\par \uc2 Editorial\par \uc2 Opinion\par \b \uc2 Congress Gets Out of the I.M.F.\u8217\'20\'19s Way\b0\par\par\uc2 By THE EDITORIAL BOARD   \par \uc2 619 \uc2 words\par \uc2 22 December 2015\par \uc2 NYTimes.com Feed\par \uc2 NYTFEED\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2015. The New York Times Company. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 After five years of Republican foot-dragging, members of Congress last week {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.imf.org/external/np/sec/pr/2015/pr15573.htm"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 ratified an agreement}}}\uc2  that will increase the capital of the \uc2 International Monetary Fund\uc2  and give developing countries like China and India a greater say in the organization. This should strengthen the fund at a time when its expertise is needed to help revive a slowing global economy.\par \par \uc2 In 2010, the Obama administration negotiated an agreement with other countries to {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/survey/so/2010/NEW110510B.htm"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 double the I.M.F.\u8217\'20\'19s capital}}}\uc2  to about $755 billion, so it could lend more money to troubled countries like Greece and Spain. The changes also gave more voting power in the fund\u8217\'20\'19s management to China, India, Brazil and Russia while slightly reducing the clout of European countries and the United States. China\u8217\'20\'19s {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.imf.org/external/np/sec/pr/2010/pdfs/pr10418_table.pdf"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 voting share }}}\uc2  would go up to 6 percent, from 3.8 percent, once the reforms began. The American share would be little changed at 16.5 percent.\par \par \uc2 Most nations quickly ratified the changes, but until recently Republicans in Congress refused to even vote on the reforms, which put the changes on hold. Some of those lawmakers argued that the fund did not need more money, while others said the organization was lending recklessly. Last week, however, the Obama administration and the Republican leaders agreed to include ratification of the I.M.F. reforms in the omnibus spending bill that the president signed on Friday.\par \par \uc2 The Republicans appear to have realized that their inaction was undermining America\u8217\'20\'19s leadership in the world. For example, China has been so frustrated that its voting share at the I.M.F. and the \uc2 World Bank\uc2  are small relative to the size of its growing economy that it has begun building its own international financial organizations. Several American allies, including Britain, Germany and \b \highlight22\uc2 South \b0 \highlight\b \highlight22\uc2 Korea\b0 \highlight\uc2 , have agreed to invest in one of those new Chinese initiatives, the \uc2 Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Congress also inserted a condition into the omnibus law that should improve the way the I.M.F. makes loans. The American representative on the fund\u8217\'20\'19s board is required to use his vote and influence with others on the board to get the I.M.F. to repeal a controversial policy that allows it to lend to countries that cannot hope to pay back all their loans when the fund\u8217\'20\'19s board determines that not making a loan would harm the global financial system.\par \par \uc2 The fund adopted {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2014-06-20/imf-considers-dropping-exemption-that-enabled-2010-greek-loan"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 this policy}}}\uc2 , which it called the \u8220\'20\'1Csystemic exception,\u8221\'20\'1D in 2010 and used it to justify lending money to Greece. Many economists and even the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/09/04/i-m-f-considers-rules-to-force-bondholders-to-share-cost-of-restructuring/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 staff of the I.M.F.}}}\uc2  have called for getting rid of it. The troubled bailout of Greece shows what happens when the fund lends money to countries that can\u8217\'20\'19t repay it. A better approach would be to call for a restructuring of debts.\par \par \uc2 The United States and European nations still need to devise a process to further increase developing countries\u8217\'20\'19 voting shares as their economies grow. And leaders in the United States and Europe need to end the anachronistic practice of appointing a European to lead the fund and an American at the \uc2 World Bank\uc2 . They should pick the best candidates regardless of nationality, including in July when the term of the managing director of the I.M.F.,{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.imf.org/external/np/omd/bios/cl.htm"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2  Christine Lagarde}}}\uc2 , a former French finance minister, ends.\par \par \uc2 If the fund and the \uc2 World Bank\uc2  are to remain relevant and be truly global organizations, they cannot be seen as European and American fiefs.\par \par \uc2 The House went into holiday recess after passing a measure that included ratification of International Monetary Fund reforms. | Zach Gibson/The New York Times   \par \par \uc2 Document NYTFEED020151222ebcm0023b\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw312\pich35\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4680\pichgoal525
