\par\par \uc2 Opinion\par \b \uc2 Japan's woeful school funding\b0\par\par\uc2 512 \uc2 words\par \uc2 20 December 2015\par \uc2 The Japan Times\par \uc2 JTIM\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9  Copyright 2015 The Japan Times. All rights reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Japan spends less on education as a percentage of gross domestic product than all the other member states of the \uc2 OECD\uc2 , it was reported in Education at a Glance 2015, a regular survey by the organization that provides data on education systems around the world. Japan's public spending amounts to just 3.5 percent of GDP, the same as Slovakia, at the bottom of the list.\par \par \uc2 This consistently and shockingly poor level of spending seems to be ignored by the central government and the education ministry. Japan's shamefully low spending, far below the \uc2 OECD\uc2  average of 4.7 percent of GDP, is an unsustainable and impossible strategy in the long run. Without sufficient support for public education, the current situation amounts to discrimination against the poor, making higher education almost unaffordable to their children.\par \par \uc2 Countries like Norway spend 6.5 percent of GDP, while Belgium and Iceland both spend 5.9 percent and New Zealand 5.4 percent. The United States and \b \highlight22\uc2 South \b0 \highlight\b \highlight22\uc2 Korea\b0 \highlight\uc2  come in at the \uc2 OECD\uc2  average of 4.7 percent. In Japan, only 34.3 percent of higher education costs are supported through public resources, half of the \uc2 OECD\uc2  average of 69.7 percent.\par \par \uc2 At primary and secondary schools, Japanese teachers have the third-biggest class size among \uc2 OECD\uc2  members. Japan's junior high schools, for example, average 32 students per class, 30 percent higher than the \uc2 OECD\uc2  average of 24 per class. Even worse, salaries of Japanese teachers with 15 years' experience have declined by 6 percent from 2008 to 2013, while most other countries increased teachers' pay during that same period. Teachers in Japan are not given much training either: the teaching practicum for Japanese secondary teachers is only 20 days, compared with 70 to 120 days in half of the other \uc2 OECD\uc2  countries.\par \par \uc2 Early childhood education is handled largely by the private sector, so that families must start paying for education from an early age. Japan has only 30 percent of children in publicly funded institutions for early education, far below the \uc2 OECD\uc2  average of 68.4 percent. Japan's 71.3 percent of pupils having to pay for private early education is strikingly high compared with the rest of the world.\par \par \uc2 Japan continues to rank rather highly in reading, information and communications technology skills, as well as problem-solving skills, and more adults than ever are receiving tertiary education. However, the gender gap between men and women remains high in Japan, with women overall more than 13 percentage points lower on all skills, the only \uc2 OECD\uc2  state with a gender differential greater than 10 percent.\par \par \uc2 Paying for education in Japan starts early and continues at a high rate for more years than other \uc2 OECD\uc2  countries. This disparity makes it clear that the current administration is doing less than ever to support education. If the nation's leaders are going to secure Japan's future, and revitalize the economy, they need to spend more on public education. In the long run, there can be no better investment.\par \par \uc2 Document JTIM000020151219ebck00002\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 EDITORIAL: Sankei journalist\u191\'00\'BFs rightful acquittal should not be used as bargaining chip\b0\par\par\uc2 by Editorial Desk in Tokyo/The Japan News/19 December 2015\par \uc2 633 \uc2 words\par \uc2 19 December 2015\par 15:02\par \uc2 ANN Asia News Network\par \uc2 ANNT\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2015. ANN   \par \par \uc2 Tokyo (The Japan News/ANN) - It was unreasonable to even indict the former \b \highlight22\uc2 Seoul\b0 \highlight\uc2  bureau chief of The Sankei Shimbun in the first place. His acquittal is a matter of course.\par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 Seoul\b0 \highlight\uc2  Central District Court has handed down a not-guilty ruling on the former bureau chief, who had been accused of the alleged defamation of South Korean President Park Geun-hye in an online article.\par \par \uc2 Although the ruling said part of the article was \u191\'00\'BFfalse," it concluded the former bureau chief was not guilty because the court \u191\'00\'BFdid not accept that the defendant intended to defame the president." The ruling pointed out that the main purpose of the article was to convey \b \highlight22\uc2 South \b0 \highlight\b \highlight22\uc2 Korea\b0 \highlight\uc2 \u191\'00\'BFs political and social situation to readers in Japan.\par \par \uc2 The article, which was published on the Sankei\u191\'00\'BFs website, quoted from a column carried in The Chosun Ilbo, a South Korean newspaper. The article reported a rumour that Park had been meeting a man on the day the Sewol passenger ship capsized off the South Korean coast in April 2014.\par \par \uc2 The former bureau chief cannot escape criticism over the fact that he carelessly mentioned a rumour in his article. However, Park is a public figure and she has means available for restoring her reputation, such as by holding a press conference to give her side of the story regarding inaccurate news coverage.\par \par \uc2 Prosecutors clearly went too far in launching a criminal prosecution based on the content of the article. This can be viewed as a politically motivated prosecution that corresponded with the wishes of the Blue House.\par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Korea\b0 \highlight\uc2  hoping to mend ties\par \par \uc2 By handing down the not-guilty ruling, the court has performed its check function against improper criminal prosecutions. However, it is certain that this ruling strongly reflected political motivations of the Park administration.\par \par \uc2 One proof of this is that before reading out the ruling, the presiding judge took the unusual step of reading out a document in which the \uc2 South Korean Foreign Ministry\uc2  asked the court to handle this case appropriately. The request called for consideration of Japan\u191\'00\'BFs position, saying, \u191\'00\'BFIn recent times, signs of improvement in ties between Japan and \b \highlight22\uc2 South \b0 \highlight\b \highlight22\uc2 Korea\b0 \highlight\uc2  have emerged."\par \par \uc2 Friday (December 18) marks the 50th anniversary of the basic treaty that normalised diplomatic relations between Japan and \b \highlight22\uc2 South \b0 \highlight\b \highlight22\uc2 Korea\b0 \highlight\uc2  coming into effect.\par \par \uc2 The timing of this milestone also probably was a factor in the court\u191\'00\'BFs decision. The ruling also might have been aimed at deflecting international criticism of the criminal prosecution.\par \par \uc2 The trial of the former bureau chief had been one impediment to improving relations between Japan and \b \highlight22\uc2 South \b0 \highlight\b \highlight22\uc2 Korea\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Last month, Park and Prime Minister \uc2 Shinzo Abe\uc2  held their first summit meeting and agreed on a plan to seek an early resolution to the so-called comfort women issue. After the court ruling was issued, a senior official of the \uc2 South Korean Foreign Ministry\uc2  said, \u191\'00\'BFWe want to use this opportunity to improve bilateral ties."\par \par \uc2 We wonder if there is expectation in \b \highlight22\uc2 South \b0 \highlight\b \highlight22\uc2 Korea\b0 \highlight\uc2  that this not-guilty ruling could lead to progress on the comfort women issue. However, it is illogical to use a judicial ruling from a completely different dimension as part of diplomatic bargaining.\par \par \uc2 The court\u191\'00\'BFs ruling was a result in line with the wishes of the Japanese government. The \uc2 Japanese Foreign Ministry\uc2  had requested that \b \highlight22\uc2 South \b0 \highlight\b \highlight22\uc2 Korea\b0 \highlight\uc2  handle this court case appropriately. After the acquittal, Abe said he hopes the decision will have \u191\'00\'BFpositive effects\u191\'00\'BF on ties between Tokyo and \b \highlight22\uc2 Seoul\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 It is important to seek improvement of the overall Japan-\b \highlight22\uc2 South \b0 \highlight\b \highlight22\uc2 Korea\b0 \highlight\uc2  relationship, without making easy compromises on the comfort women issue.\par \par \uc2 COPYRIGHT: \uc2 ASIA NEWS NETWORK\par \par \uc2 Document ANNT000020151219ebcj00008\par }\par }}